<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / International Company News: First-quarter loss at MIM
Holdings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE continuing slump in base metals prices has pushed Brisbane-based MIM
Holdings to a first-quarter after-tax loss of ADollars 30.4m (USDollars
20.3m) in the 12 weeks to September 19, compared with a profit of ADollars
29m a year ago, writes Nikki Tait.
At the operating level, the international metals group saw an after-tax
deficit of ADollars 6.9m, down from last time's profit of ADollars 34.5m.
The final result was further depressed by ADollars 17.8m due to a write-off
of cash contributed by MIM to its joint-venture smelting operations in
Germany.
The company said that sales volumes rose in some areas - 18 per cent higher
for lead, 28 per cent for zinc, and 41 per cent for coal - although copper
was down 10 per cent and gold by 24 per cent.
But base metals prices fell in Australian dollar terms, with zinc - down 38
per cent - showing the largest year-on-year decline.
Gold and silver prices were stronger, but total sales revenue for the
quarter still slipped by 9 per cent.
</TEXT>
