<DATE>931026
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / Bidders dig deep to stage final showdown: The rising stakes
in the battle for Paramount
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
How much is Mr Barry Diller, chairman of the television home shopping group
QVC Network, prepared to pay to snatch Paramount Communications away from
its engagement to Viacom, the cable television company?
That is the central question facing Paramount shareholders this week,
following Sunday night's move by Viacom to increase the value of its agreed
bid for the company from Dollars 7.5bn to Dollars 9.5bn, thus matching the
value of QVC's hostile offer. The move sweeps aside the financial edge QVC
has enjoyed since it entered the fray on September 20, with a Dollars 9.5bn
proposal.
And it leaves Viacom with a slight upper hand: it has the agreement of the
Paramount board to a merger, and the two marriage partners are advanced in
obtaining the necessary regulatory clearances.
Viacom also has the advantage of 'lock-up' provisions that allow it to buy
20 per cent of Paramount's stock at Dollars 69.14 a share and receive a
Dollars 100m payment from Paramount if its bid does not go through.
'The ball is in QVC's court to decide whether to step aside or raise its
offer,' says Ms Margo Vignola, an analyst at Salomon Brothers.
It was Mr Diller, a prominent film industry figure, who increased the tempo
of the contest last Thursday when, frustrated by the Paramount board's
reluctance to open negotiations, he changed the terms of QVC's bid proposal,
while maintaining the overall value.
First, he announced that QVC would proceed this week with a cash tender
offer for 51 per cent of Paramount's shares, at Dollars 80 a share, costing
Dollars 4.8bn. It would buy the remaining 49 per cent in a later stock-swap
tender, also valued at around Dollars 80 a share.
The move had two important elements. First, it raised the amount of cash in
the QVC offer from Dollars 3.5bn to Dollars 4.8bn - shareholders generally
prefer to receive cash. Second, by launching a tender, QVC by-passed the
Paramount board and took its offer directly to the shareholders. The
manoeuvre left Viacom with no alternative but to increase its offer. It
therefore launched a tender offer on Sunday on the same terms as QVC, and
offered to buy the remaining 49 per cent in a second stage tender at Dollars
80 a share in a mixture of common and preferred stock.
Ms Jessica Reif, an analyst at Oppenheimer &amp; Co, says this leaves Mr Diller
with three choices: 'He can increase the cash portion of his bid, he can
increase the total value above Dollars 80, or he can walk away. But given
the scarcity value of the assets I think walking away is the least likely.'
But how much more can either QVC (with revenues of around Dollars 1bn) or
Viacom (revenues Dollars 2bn) afford to pay for the much larger Paramount
(revenues of Dollars 4bn)?
Their offers are already far from cheap - Ms Reif puts them at around 19
times Paramount's 1993 operating cash flow and 36 times its earnings. With
Dollars 4.8bn in cash on the table, both companies appear to be getting
close to the limits of their war chests.
QVC's armoury contains around Dollars 5bn, consisting of Dollars 3bn in bank
loan commitments and Dollars 500m of equity investments from four other
media companies: Comcast, Liberty Media (both of which are already large QVC
shareholders), Cox Enterprises and Advance Publications.
Viacom's new offer was made possible by a Dollars 1.2bn equity commitment
from Nynex, the Baby Bell telephone company, and a further Dollars 600m from
Blockbuster Entertainment, the video rental business. It must also have
lined up some Dollars 3bn in bank borrowings.
However, in addition to the war-chests, the protagonist gaining control of
Paramount will have access to that company's Dollars 1bn in cash reserves,
giving each side some latitude to increase its offer. Either side might also
persuade their media backers, or bankers, to provide some extra money.
Certainly, takeover battles have a habit of soaring out of the bounds of
rational financial considerations, and Paramount is such a rare prize - one
of the last of the large, independent Hollywood film studios - that the
bidding seems certain to go higher, be it from QVC, Viacom or an entirely
new entrant to the fray.
The heads of all three companies have a great deal riding on the outcome.
For 70-year-old Mr Sumner Redstone, chairman of Viacom, the deal is a chance
to cap his career in style - although he vowed yesterday not to carry out
'an excessively leveraged transaction'.
For Mr Diller, it is an opportunity to turn QVC from a humble television
home shopping business into a leading US entertainment concern. Mr Martin
Davis, chairman of Paramount, is anxious to complete the friendly deal with
Viacom and avoid being swallowed by QVC. He and Mr Diller are bitter
enemies.
The only thing that can be said with certainty is that the battle is far
from over. Few shareholders will be interested in the tender offer when even
better terms seem likely to be on the table before too long.
Lex, Page 16; Flextech in talks with TCI, page 24
THE BIDDING WAR FOR PARAMOUNT
September 12: Viacom's agreed Dollars 8.2bn cash and shares bid for
Paramount.
Fall in Viacom's shares reduces value of bid to Dollars 7.5bn. Paramount's
shares soar on speculation of rival bid
September 20: QVC Network launches hostile cash-and shares bid worth Dollars
9.5bn. Paramount stands by preference for Viacom
October 4: Viacom gains Dollars 1.2bn investment from Nynex, adding to the
Dollars 600m put up by Blockbuster Entertainment
October 5: QVC says Dollars 4bn funding arranged, includes Dollars 500m each
in equity investments from Comcast and Liberty Media (re-merging with
Tele-Communications Inc), plus commitments from six banks
October 17: QVC gains further Dollars 1bn through investments by Advance
Publications and Cox Enterprises
October 21: QVC makes Dollars 4.8bn cash tender offer - Dollars 80 a share -
for 51 per cent of Paramount, increasing cash element of hostile bid
October 24: Viacom launches similar cash tender offer at Dollars 80 a share
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>QVC Network Inc.
    Paramount Communications Inc.
    Viacom International Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
