<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / Pounds 2bn 'raves'pose threat to leisure spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RAVES are now a Pounds 2bn a year industry challenging established leisure
industries according to a study by the Henley Centre, the research and
forecasting organisation, released yesterday.
Over a million young people a week in the UK are now going to 'rave' parties
and spending an average of Pounds 35 a head on the activity, the study
reveals.
The 'staggering' spending figure - much of it on illegal drugs - is about
the same size as the books or newspaper markets, and at least a quarter of
the spirits market, says Henley. The study excludes unlicensed raves.
The parties, which are held in warehouses and halls within easy reach of
metropolitan areas, commonly attract 4,000-10,000 young people at a time, a
large proportion of whom are under 21 years of age. Raves are usually
alcohol-free but there is normally heavy consumption of drugs, says the
centre.
Raves 'pose a significant threat to spending for such sectors as licenced
drinks retailers and drinks companies,' says the study. Pub visits by young
people fell 11 per cent between 1987 and 1991 and Henley is forecasting a
further decline of 9 per cent during 1992-97.
Henley calculates that the average admission charge to a rave is Pounds 15;
spending on drugs is typically Pounds 3-Pounds 5 for LSD; Pounds 15 for
ecstasy; Pounds 5 for speed; Pounds 15 for cannabis; mineral water is Pounds
1 a bottle; and cigarettes cost Pounds 3.
The report says it is clear that the minimum spend at a rave is about Pounds
20 and the maximum could be about Pounds 50. Henley uses an average figure
of Pounds 35 a visit per person to produce a weekly spending total of Pounds
35m for the million participants. The percentage of 16-24-year-olds taking
illegal drugs has doubled to nearly 30 per cent over the three years to
1992, says the report.
Raves are also extremely time-consuming, displacing time and energy 'which
might have been expended on other leisure activities'. Raves can last
anywhere between eight and 24 hours, and a weekend rave can go on for 48-72
hours.
Leisure Futures volume 3. Henley Centre, 9 Bridewell Place, London EC4V 6AY.
Pounds 375
</TEXT>
