<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / Citibank appeals over Pounds 14m payout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Court of Appeal yesterday began hearing an appeal by Citibank against a
High Court ruling that it should pay Pounds 14.7m compensation to Smith New
Court, the securities house, for losses incurred on the purchase of Ferranti
shares worth Pounds 23m.
The 28m shares were bought in July 1989, shortly before the discovery of a
fraud on Ferranti halved the value of the stock.
The High Court held in March last year that SNC's bid price for the shares
had been induced by fraudulent misrepresentations made to it by Mr
Christopher Roberts, the then head of private banking at Citibank, part of
the US Citicorp group, and a director of Scrimgeour Vickers (Asset
Management), its marketmakers.
Mr Roberts had falsely told SNC it was competing with two other bidders, Mr
Justice Chadwick had said at the hearing. SNC was awarded Pounds 10.7m
compensation plus interest of about Pounds 4m.
Mr Jonathan Sumption QC, for Citibank, yesterday argued that the judge had
made a finding of fraud against Mr Roberts without adequate foundation.
Mr Sumption said a high standard of proof was needed to support the
allegation of fraud - especially since Mr Roberts was acquitted of similar
criminal charges.
SNC's allegations were always based upon evidence given by two of its
directors, Mr Lewis and Mr Abrahams, who were primarily responsible for the
transaction, Mr Sumption said. Mr Justice Chadwick had regarded both men as
discredited witnesses whereas he made no adverse finding about the
credibility of Mr Roberts.
The judge's finding of fraud was therefore substantially based on
speculative inferences. This was a wholly inappropriate basis on which to
make the grave finding of fraud, Mr Sumption said.
The case is due to last 10 days.
</TEXT>
