<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / Legal battle launched over Isuzu imports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IM GROUP, Britain's largest private motor-import business, is to serve a
writ against General Motors and its Vauxhall subsidiary over their plans to
take over import and distribution of Isuzu vehicles in the UK from January.
Mr Bob Edmiston's IM, whose wholly owned Isuzu (UK) subsidiary has held the
Isuzu franchise since 1987, declared its intention to serve the writ after
Vauxhall's chairman, Mr Charles Golden, said Vauxhall would 'take up its
right' to import Isuzu's four-wheel-drive Trooper model from January 1.
IM's dispute with General Motors centres on its allegations that General
Motors unlawfully sought to procure the termination of Isuzu (UK)'s contract
to operate the franchise in the UK.
IM originally filed a suit against General Motors in the US, but a US court
ruled last month that any proceedings should be heard in the UK, and that
General Motors should make available any documents and witnesses considered
necessary.
Specifically, it is seeking to retain its right to market the Isuzu Trooper
four-wheel-drive vehicle, in spite of the contention of General Motors -
which has a 37 per cent stake in Isuzu - that IM had agreed to relinquish
the franchise at the end of this year.
According to IM, Isuzu (UK) has also instructed lawyers in Japan to obtain
an injunction from a Tokyo court preventing the termination of the
concession by the Japanese company. Isuzu in Japan has refused to comment on
the dispute.
Under General Motors' plans, the Trooper will be sold through the Vauxhall
cars network from the beginning of next year, badged as the Vauxhall
Monterey.
General Motors has been selling the vehicle through its Continental European
dealer networks, where it is badged as an Opel, since early last year.
Mr Golden insisted: 'Any litigation will not delay the launch of the
Monterey.'
But Mr Edmiston said: 'If General Motors and Vauxhall think they can now
brush us aside and carry off the Trooper without a fight they are much
mistaken.'
In the meantime IM has been negotiating to obtain the concession for further
four-wheel-drive vehicles and is understood to be close to a final agreement
to import Korean-built Ssangyong vehicles to the UK from late next year.
IM has already signed a letter of intent with Ssangyong, whose new off-road
vehicle, the FJ, was unveiled at the recent Frankfurt motor show. The
vehicles are powered by Mercedes-Benz engines and have been designed by a
British designer.
IM is also the importer of Japanese Subaru cars and until earlier this year
held the import concession for Hyundai, Korea's largest carmaker.
However in July it signed a deal with the Lex Service group giving Lex a a
50.1 per cent stake in Hyundai Car (UK), a new joint-venture company with IM
which acquired an exclusive rolling three-year contract to import Hyundais
from last month.
</TEXT>
