<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / Hostility to Jews 'less in Britain'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ATTITUDES towards Jews in Britain are more positive than those towards other
minorities, says a survey by Gallup for the American Jewish Committee, the
international lobby group.
The survey of 959 people, which was published yesterday and is part of an
international series, also showed that hostility towards Jews was less in
Britain than in many other countries, including the US.
Dr David Singer, director of research for the committee, said the results
were encouraging but he noted that 25 per cent of those questioned still
thought that anti-Semitism would increase in the fut-ure.
Eight per cent of respondents thought Jews behaved in a way which provoked
hostility. This compared with 57 per cent who felt this about Gypsies, 28
per cent about Pakistanis, 26 per cent about West Indians and 21 per cent
about Arabs.
Asked if Jews had too much influence in British society, 8 per cent said
they did, 42 per cent said they had the 'right amount' of influence, and 7
per cent 'too little'. On the extent of anti-Semitism, the survey found that
45 per cent felt it was 'not a problem at all'.
International comparisons show that 28 per cent in Austria think Jews have
too much influence, compared with 20 per cent in the US, and 5 per cent in
the former Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
