<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / Mental healthcare strategy attacked
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN is relying on an 'inadequate, piecemeal approach' to mental
healthcare and ignoring the experience of other countries, the King's Fund
Institute said yesterday.
The health think-tank made several recommendations in a report published
yesterday, including the drawing up of national 'goals' for mental
healthcare.
Ms Judy Turner-Crowson, a former US health official, said the care of
mentally ill people in the community could be transformed if policymakers
learned lessons from the US.
She added: 'The central problem in both countries has been the patchy, slow
and uneven development of community services to take the place of the old
mental hospitals.'
Services could only be properly developed if a framework of action were
agreed by the mentally ill people and their families, health professionals,
managers and policymakers, she said.
The problems in Britain have been made worse by the large number of
different professionals responsible for caring for the mentally ill. Cash
shortages coupled with plans to create smaller local authorities pose a
threat to Care in the Community policies, Dr Gary Craig, a health policy
expert, said in a report yesterday. He said the changes would weaken social
services, endangering services such as meals-on-wheels and home-helps in
some areas.
</TEXT>
