<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / Unions criticised over training and flexibility
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   David Goodhart, Labour Editor
UNIONS fail to take the lead in vital workplace activities such as training,
fostering workplace flexibility and employee involvement, says a submission
to the Commons employment committee inquiry into the future of unions which
begins its hearings today.
The submission, from the Involvement and Participation Association, an
organisation supported by both unions and employers, also says that unions
could expand their work on individual grievance issues.
'Employees need more support over redundancy procedures, abuse of employee
rights and individual contract bargaining,' the IPA says.
The association stresses that employee involvement is not dependent on
unions, and points to the John Lewis Partnership and Black &amp; Decker as
non-union companies with model involvement systems.
Yet it also says that individual and collective representation are not
alternatives and should complement each other. 'There is a continuing need
for a collective voice but if trade unions are to play a beneficial role
when the recession lifts they will have to adapt very rapidly to the changes
which surround them,' the association says.
It states that unions have two main roles: first, as guardians of individual
rights and providers of individual services to members; and second as
providers of an employee 'voice'. It adds: 'Change is only possible today
with employee support, and it is essential for survival. Unions have a
particularly important role to play in creating a better balance between job
security and job flexibility.'
It believes unions should lobby for the maintenance of training budgets and
employee involvement activities when times are hard. Unions should also
encourage their members to develop mobile skills, thereby giving them
greater flexibility.
At today's first hearing the Trades Union Congress will call for a change in
the law to give workers a legal right to be represented by a union.
The TUC says world-class companies recognise unions and that unions in
Britain, as in Germany and Japan, are committed to the best standards in
employment as the basis for producing the best goods and services.
Workers in unions, says the TUC, have better wages and conditions and are
better protected against arbitrary employer action.
The casualised labour force of the 1990s lacks power in the labour market
and so has a greater need for unions, it says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
