<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / Regulator will oversee running of gas auctions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OFFICE of Fair Trading yesterday confirmed that it had given Ofgas, the
gas industry regulator, responsibility for overseeing the auctions of gas
from British Gas stockpiles.
The changeover comes after complaints that increasing numbers of speculators
were attracted to the auctions, which were intended to stimulate early
competition in the market by making British Gas supplies available to the
new independent gas companies.
The supply of such 'release gas' was intended to be a temporary solution,
which would allow the new companies to attract customers while they
developed their own offshore gas sources or negotiated long-term contracts
from North Sea producers.
Ofgas has told the industry that it will introduce checks to ensure that
speculators are excluded in future. Mr Kristoffer Maroe, managing director
of Alliance Gas, the joint venture between BP, Statoil, the Norwegian state
oil company, and Norsk Hydro, yesterday welcomed the change.
'In the last auction more than 100 companies were allocated release gas,' he
said, 'but only 30 or so actually made transportation agreements with
British Gas.'
The importance of the auctions is likely to diminish in future as more gas
becomes available to the independents. In addition, a secondary market is
emerging and Mr Maroe said it was 'now possible to sell or acquire spot
gas'.
British Gas said yesterday that it had been expecting the transfer of
regulatory responsibilities. The company will meet Ofgas shortly to make
arrangements for future sales.
</TEXT>
