<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / BCCI payout unlikely until August
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CREDITORS of the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce International are
unlikely to receive any payments until at least August next year, it emerged
yesterday.
A first dividend of 15p in the pound cannot be paid unless an agreement
between the liquidators and the government of Abu Dhabi, the majority
shareholder in the bank, is ratified by the Luxembourg court of appeal.
A verdict is expected tomorrow in an appeal by three BCCI depositors against
the ratification of the agreement by a lower court last year. If the appeal
fails, accountants at Touche Ross, BCCI liquidators, can proceed with a
ballot of creditors to approve a contribution of at least Dollars 1.7bn
(Pounds 1.14bn) from Abu Dhabi in exchange for a waiver of legal action
against it.
Touche Ross warned that a payout in August next year was its most optimistic
assessment and that a further appeal to Luxembourg's highest court could
take the distribution of a first dividend into 1995.
Mr Hal Skolnick, Mr Adil Elias and Mr Assilaos Artiki, the appellants, will
have six months to appeal against tommorrow's judgment if it goes against
them, which would defer payments further.
If their appeal succeeds, however, Touche Ross will have to consider
launching its own appeal, suing Abu Dhabi or renegotiating its agreement.
Even if the court of appeal finds in favour of Touche, the firm said it
would need to obtain approval from at least Dollars 4.75bn-worth of
creditors before proceeding with its agreement with Abu Dhabi.
Total fees incurred by Touche Ross in the worldwide liquidation have reached
approximately Pounds 100m, up from Pounds 86m at the start of the year.
The Luxembourg court is also expected to announce tomorrow that an appeal
against a separate pooling agreement between BCCI liquidators in different
countries has been dropped.
That will clear the way for Touche Ross to negotiate with other
jurisdictions on the distribution of any dividends.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
