<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / Concession offered on BR pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MacGregor, transport secretary, yesterday tried to win over Tory MPs
sceptical about rail privatisation by offering a concession over BR's
pension fund.
In a letter to Tory backbenchers, Mr MacGregor said the government would
seek agreement with British Rail's pension-fund trustees before putting
proposals before parliament. The move follows the government's defeat in the
Lords over its plans to water down its obligations on Treasury contributions
to the fund.
The Lords passed an amendment tabled by Lord Peyton, a former Conservative
transport minister, which would re-impose an obligation on the government to
secure the trustees' written agreement before altering its financial
commitments.
Lord Caithness, transport minister, had argued the amendment would in effect
give the pension-fund managers a veto over government expenditure. He said
the obligation should be to consult the trustees.
In his letter, Mr MacGregor says: 'The government's obligations will be
reflected as an asset of pension funds and taken into account in determining
any surplus for pensions. We intend to agree the details of such an
arrangement with the trustees and we will bring before parliament in due
course orders which will give effect to such agreement.'
Mr Andrew Bowden, MP for Brighton Kemptown and one of the backbenchers who
forced the government to climb down over pensioners' railcards, said he
would support the sell-off bill, but with reservations. He said: 'I am
delighted that the government is bringing appropriate orders before
parliament to protect the pension fund.'
Mr Tim Rathbone, MP for Lewes and another backbench sceptic, also welcomed
Mr MacGregor's assurances.
Ministers, however, made clear last night that their concession did not mean
they would accept the amendment in full. This is why some MPs remained
sceptical about how far the government was prepared to go in accepting Lord
Peyton's amendment.
Rebel Tory MPs are also threatening to back an earlier Lords' amendment
allowing BR to bid for the franchises under which the network will be
gradually privatised.
Mr Rathbone said the government had nothing to fear since ministers had been
successful in attracting proposals for management buy-outs when it was not
known whether BR could bid for the franchises.
Letters, Page 18
</TEXT>
