<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / UN warns Haiti of new sanctions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KINGSTON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations Security Council yesterday threatened additional
sanctions against Haiti's military rulers unless an accord calling for the
restoration of deposed President Jean-Bertrand Aristide was fully
implemented.
The new warning was announced as UN special envoy Dante Caputo continued
intensive efforts in Haiti aimed at Mr Aristide's return by a Saturday
deadline.
Mr Aristide's return was originally agreed as part of a United
Nations-brokered plan aimed at restoring Haiti to democracy. The plan was
signed on New York's Governor Island last July by Mr Aristide and army chief
General Raoul Cedras, who overthrew him in a 1991 coup.
The threatened new sanctions would include a complete trade embargo, on top
of an arms and oil ban and a freeze on financial assets that were reimposed
last week.
Haitian legislators will begin debate today on new laws proposed by
pro-military parliamentarians, which would include a broad amnesty for all
political crimes committed since the military forced Mr Aristide out two
years ago.
Legislators are also to consider the broadening of Mr Aristide's cabinet to
include supporters of the military, and legislation to separate the army and
the police. 'It is essential the parliament meets (today),' Mr Caputo said
yesterday.
Mr Robert Malval, the premier appointed by Mr Aristide, and Gen Cedras, the
army leader, met last night to discuss Gen Cedras' undertaking to step aside
as soon as parliament ratifies the new laws, but little progress was made in
the talks and the two will meet again on Wednesday.
There are doubts that MPs who support Mr Aristide will attend parliament
today. Most went into hiding a fortnight ago when an armed gang, held to be
supporters of the military, invaded parliament and abducted some members.
</TEXT>
