<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / Poland's coalition selects cabinet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POLAND'S coalition partners last night agreed on a cabinet only hours before
its formal presentation today to President Lech Walesa.
Five hours of tense negotiations between the Left Democratic Alliance (SLD)
and the Polish Peasant Party (PSL) saw Mr Waldemar Pawlak, prime minister
and PSL leader, drop his nominee for privatisation minister in favour of Mr
Wieslaw Kaczmarek, a banker from the SLD free market wing.
Earlier in the day Mr Pawlak had unveiled a list without consulting the SLD
and giving his party control of more economic ministries than his coalition
partners had previously agreed to accept.
The new ministers are expected to be sworn in by Mr Walesa today. However,
the coalition will have to win a vote of confidence within two weeks in
parliament where they control two-thirds of the seats following last month's
election.
Mr Marek Borowski, a former internal trade minister from the SLD, will be
finance minister and deputy premier responsible for the economy; Mr
Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz, also an SLD supporter, is to be justice minister
and deputy premier responsible for social policy; Mr Alexander Luczak from
the PSL will be education minister and deputy premier responsible for
defence, internal and foreign affairs; Mr Andrzej Milczanowski remains
interior minister; Mr Andrzej Olechowski becomes foreign minister; and
Admiral Piotr Kolodziejczyk gets defence.
</TEXT>
