<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 93 / Benefit fraud costs Pounds 5bn a year, say officials
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN Pounds 5bn a year of government money may be lost through
fraudulent benefit claims, according to Whitehall officials investigating
abuse of the social security system.
Officials say the investigation, launched earlier this year, has uncovered
far greater abuse of state welfare than had been thought, with many examples
of improper claims for old age pensions, unemployment assistance and child
benefit. Until recently, ministers had estimated that the state lost some
Pounds 1bn a year in fraudulent claims. But officials say the investigation
 -by four Department of Social Security officials under the aegis of the
Whitehall efficiency unit, set up to uncover wasteful government expenditure
 -has produced evidence of fraud on a much greater scale.
'The study shows that the amount of benefit fraud is much higher than
expected,' said one official yesterday. 'It would not be wrong to say that
the figure is in excess of Pounds 5bn per year.' That compares with an total
annual bill for welfare benefit of around Pounds 80bn.
The scale of benefit fraud is being cited by ministers as the principal
reason for considering the introduction of an identity card system for
benefit claimants. If implemented, this would be the first time the state
has required British citizens to carry any form of formal identification
other than a passport.
Civil liberties groups have strongly opposed such a move as an infringement
of individual rights. But DSS officials did not rule out the possibility
yesterday that the ID card system could be introduced for all 21m benefit
claimants.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, said yesterday that the
introduction of an identity card system would depend on the final
presentation of the efficiency unit's report, due in a month. But Downing
Street officials say the introduction of an identity card system is backed
by Mr John Major, the prime minister, who has closely monitored the
investigation.
Officials said that, to overcome civil liberties concerns, the information
stored on an identity card would be 'of no use to the police'.
The favoured identification method would involve social security and pension
claimants having some form of 'hand scan', he said. The hand image would
then be stored electronically on a card.
This would allow the cardholder's identity to be ascertained with an error
factor of one in 100,000 - enough to prevent an individual drawing money
with a stolen card, but a certainty factor too low to be used in a court of
law.
</TEXT>
