<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / International Company News: Viacom raises bid to step up
battle for Paramount
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE TAKEOVER battle for Paramount Communications, the film and publishing
group, intensified last night when Viacom, the cable television company,
raised the value of its friendly bid to match a Dollars 4.8bn cash tender
offer for 51 per cent of Paramount announced on Thursday by hostile bidder
QVC Network.
Viacom, acting with the agreement of the Paramount board, said it too would
begin a cash tender offer for 51 per cent of the company's shares, starting
today, at a price of Dollars 80 a share.
The remainder of Paramount's shares would be acquired later in a stock swap,
also worth around Dollars 80 a share on the basis of Viacom's shares at
Friday's stock market close.
The new bid appeared to value Paramount at around Dollars 9.5bn, roughly the
same as QVC's offer, though last night Viacom claimed its bid to be worth
about Dollars 10bn. Viacom's initial bid was worth around Dollars 7.5bn.
The increased bid had been widely expected on Wall Street since QVC forced
the pace of the battle last Thursday with the announcement of its cash
tender for Paramount's shares, due to start by this Wednesday.
Viacom, by offering the same terms as QVC in its tender, will be hoping that
shareholders will be won over by the fact that its bid has the agreement of
the Paramount board, and by the claims of synergy made by the two companies.
However, many shareholders seem likely to hold back, in the expectation that
the bidding still has some way to escalate.
Viacom's new offer sharply increases the amount of cash in its bid, from
around Dollars 1.1bn to Dollars 4.8bn. The stock-swap element of the deal
would involve 0.2048 of a share of Viacom class A voting stock, 1.08317 of
Viacom Class B non-voting stock, and 0.20408 of a share of new convertible
exchangeable preferred stock, for each share in Paramount.
The boards of the two companies said their amended merger agreement also
gave them the flexibility to go ahead with a single stage merger
transaction, rather than the new two-stage deal, if they wanted to do so.
Viacom said the new preferred stock would have the same yield, conversion
price and call protection as the Dollars 600m of preferred shares it
recently sold to Blockbuster Entertainment, the video rental chain, and the
Dollars 1.2bn sold to Nynex, the Baby Bell telephone company.
The financial backing of these two companies boosted Viacom's war chest,
helping it to launch yesterday's higher offer.
</TEXT>
