<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Entrepreneur avoids advance-fee disaster: What happened to a
young businessman when he tried to raise funding for his computer company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NAJAM Ul-Hasan Kidwai, fresh out of university, was one of the lucky
ones. Like most of Turnberry Underwriter's customers he paid them a retainer
to procure finance. Unlike many others, he managed to reclaim his fee.
Within days of being put in contact with Turnberry, Mr Kidwai, 24, found
himself embroiled in a saga which took him from the sober setting of
Sunderland to Miami's flashy financial districts where businessmen
hypnotised him with talk of multi-million pound loan schemes.
Mr Kidwai's story begins with Cybereye, a computer development company he
set up earlier this year to exploit the potential for virtual reality in the
medical, education and computer-aided design fields. Cybereye needed cash to
take its ideas from the drawing board to reality.
With little prospect of help through conventional means - largely because of
his youth and lack of a track record, according to those who turned him down
for financing - Mr Kidwai turned to classified advertisements in national
newspaper columns. Here he came across EFG, a New York company which acts as
an agent for Turnberry.
Mr Kidwai was asked to fly to Miami to discuss his business proposal with a
team from Turnberry. Mr Kidwai was impressed by Turnberry's image. The plush
Miami office was sited next to US investment bank Smith Barney.
The next day, after examining his business plan, Turnberry offered to
syndicate Dollars 8m in funding for Cybereye in return for a retainer of
Dollars 100,000. The retainer, to cover Turnberry's costs, was to be held in
escrow by a Florida solicitor, Mr Jerrell Breslin. It has emerged that at
that time Mr Breslin was under investigation by the FBI. He has since been
arrested and charged with conspiring to sell US Treasury bonds stolen from a
New York savings bank. He is on bail.
Mr Kidwai was told that Turnberry could provide collateral in the form of
treasury bills, cash or other instruments which would allow Cybereye to
raise a one-year bank loan of Dollars 8m. However, the security would not be
available until the UK company had arranged a letter of credit payable to
Turnberry for Dollars 1.5m - or 20 per cent of the total loan. This was to
be Turnberry's return for providing the collateral.
At the end of the year, if Cybereye was unable to repay the loan, the
collateral would belong to the lending bank. But Cybereye's ability to repay
the loan would be virtually guaranteed by a flotation of 35 per cent of the
company on a Latin American stock exchange arranged through a financial
company introduced by Turnberry, Les Mersky Associates. The financial
company would be able to float the stock at whatever price it wished and
keep anything in excess of Dollars 8m.
Mr Kidwai was unaware that Mr Leslie Mersky, of Les Mersky Associates, was
president of Turnberry. Nor did he know that Mr Mersky, like Mr Breslin, was
under investigation for alleged fraud, this time by the Securities and
Exchange Commission. Last year Mr Mersky and several others were accused of
allegedly distri-buting and manipulating shares in a shell corporation,
which was said to have made a fraudulent stock offering. The case is still
pending.
Mr Kidwai believed the deal he was being offered was flawless. For a mere
Dollars 100,000 he would get a one-year bridging loan. Turnberry would get
Dollars 1.6m, including the retainer, out of the Dollars 8m loan and the
collateral would revert to the US company after a year.
Cybereye, which only ever intended to draw down Dollars 1m of the Dollars 8m
facility, would be able to repay the loan through proceeds raised by the
flotation. Cybereye's bankers also had a gold-plated guarantee, since they
would hold collateral provided by Turnberry worth Dollars 8m, and could
foreclose after a year if the loan was not repaid from the flotation
proceeds. Further comfort was taken from the fact that only Dollars 2.6m of
the Dollars 8m facility would be drawn in the year.
However, this was a deal which - even given an unusually extended deadline
for completion of 40 days - proved impossible to complete. While Cybereye
managed to find bankers prepared to issue the letter of guarantee and
provide the banking loan, everything hinged on proving that the collateral
was ready to be transferred. No bank would issue a letter of credit to
Turnberry until it was sure the collateral was on its way.
Cybereye's bank contacted the Guardian Bank and Trust (Cayman) Ltd, a
private bank based in the Cayman Islands, which it had been told was
Turnberry's bankers. It was informed over the phone that funds for the
collateral were available. But the bank needed more precise details before
releasing the letter of credit. It sought reassurance that Turnberry's
collateral came from 'good, clean funds of non-criminal origin, and that
this statement was issued under the penalty of perjury'. But Turnberry
insisted there was 'no bank in the world . . . who can legitimately' make
such a statement.
Several attempts by Cybereye and its bankers to find a compromise to end the
deadlock were rejected by Turnberry. It soon became apparent that no deal
would be completed in the time allowed.
Mr Kidwai, frustrated by repeated fruitless attempts to contact Turnberry
and faced with the almost certain loss of his Dollars 100,000 retainer,
contacted the authorities. He issued a letter headed 'fraud alert'
containing his account of his dealings with Turnberry, Mr Breslin, Guardian
Bank &amp; Trust (Cayman) Ltd, and Les Mersky. Guardian Bank &amp; Trust (Cayman)
Ltd then threatened Mr Kidwai with legal action unless he retracted the
statements made in the letter. Mr Kidwai demanded the return of his retainer
from Turnberry who notified him he was in default of the agreement, which
would result in the loss of his retainer. Mr Kidwai eventually issued a
retraction and his retainer was returned.
Today Mr Kidwai is still searching for a backer. The months of delay in
negotiating with Turnberry have almost crippled his company, which operates
out of the Industry Centre in Sunderland University. But he is determined
not to give up, nor to let others get into the difficulties which he so
narrowly avoided.
Other companies in the US and UK have had similar experiences with
Turnberry. Such difficulties have now attracted the interest of the FBI and
UK authorities, who are investigating Turnberry's activities.
</TEXT>
<XX>
