<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / BBC plans bi-media staff shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC is pushing ahead with plans to make news and current affairs staff
interchangeable between radio and television through the creation of a
single management structure.
Mr Peter Bell, now editor of television news programmes, will from the
beginning of January head all news programmes across radio and television.
A new bi-media head of all weekly programmes will be appointed later this
year.
Mr Tony Hall, managing director of news and current affairs, believes the
move will increase efficiency and get more programmes made for the same
money.
He added: 'There is no increase in management at all. We have re-allocated
people's tasks.'
Mr Hall became convinced of the wisdom of the bi-media approach the night Mr
John Major won the Conservative leadership battle.
A television outside-broadcast unit and a radio car were simultaneously
dispatched to cover the story. The radio car broke down and the OB unit
provided the necessary sound interviews.
Mr Hall believes the bi-media policy will lead to 'a free market in ideas'
throughout BBC news and current affairs and improve strategic planning
across both radio and television.
With investigative stories the most appropriate medium will be chosen, he
said. A successful radio programme could lead to a television programme.
'I don't see this approach happening at ITV. No one else can do this,' said
Mr Hall.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Broadcasting Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4832 Radio Broadcasting Stations.
    P4833 Television Broadcasting Stations.
