<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / A few home truths from Clarke's backyard: Michael Cassell
listens to the advice being offered to the chancellor by his Nottinghamshire
constituents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH CLARKE can dismiss the pre-Budget petitioning of his 'seven wise
men'. As for the avalanche of advice from 57 varieties of vested interest -
who needs it?
But if the chancellor wants a few home truths before Budget day, he knows
where to go to have his ear bent: to his own Nottinghamshire constituency of
Rushcliffe and to Mr Ray Cook, a 64-year-old retired bank manager rich in
anecdotes and homespun philosophy. Like his MP, Mr Cook speaks his mind.
'You couldn't have a better person pulling the cart; he can take the flak.
But he must cut interest rates, concentrate on measures to help wealth
creation, then take a deep breath and wait for the benefits of the upturn to
work through.
'There is no point in imposing extra taxes now and wrecking the recovery
just to start paying off the interest on Pounds 50bn worth of debt. The only
real way to cut the deficit is to get the economy growing.'
Mr Cook has more than a passing interest in the chancellor's performance,
given his role as leader of Rushcliffe borough council.
The councillor's call for a 'softly softly' Budget - he has known Mr Clarke
for 20 years - wins widespread support across the constituency, representing
157 square miles of rich farmland and busy villages which stretch south and
east from the Trent Bridge county cricket ground on the edge of Nottingham.
Last year its voters gave Mr Clarke a near-21,000 majority. These from the
Cuckoo Bush pub in Gotham to the Fish Bar in Ruddington, where locals claim
the chancellor has queued for his fix of chips, are telling Mr Clarke to lay
off.
Rushcliffe - 'all fur coats and Waterford crystal' to its neighbours - has
not been as badly savaged by recession as many other areas. White-collar
redundancies have helped push up unemployment to about 9 per cent, although
it is twice that level in Nottingham.
Earlier this year, however, the Cotgrave pit - which a decade ago employed
nearly 2,000 people - mined its last coal, and miners have left the area or
signed on.
But there are some indications that employers in Rushcliffe are again
recruiting, that shops are busier and that a housing market which avoided
the full horrors of the slump has started to move. Mr Jim Collinson, a
member of Rushcliffe's planning team, said: 'Architects have been sitting on
their hands for two years but now they are getting lots of inquiries.
Development plans are being dusted off.'
Recovery, however, remains a fragile affair which the locals believe could
easily be smashed by too heavy a hand from the ordinary
bloke-turned-chancellor who lives out along the Melton Road.
'He must not meddle. There is an improvement under way but the picture
remains very mixed and vulnerable,' said Mr John Moy, finance director of
NSK-RHP (Europe), the Japanese-owned bearings manufacturer. The company
recently announced that Ruddington is to be home for its European
headquarters and sales organisation, a decision which could mean more than
170 new jobs.
Mr Moy added: 'We need still lower interest rates to help maintain new
levels of investment. Our domestic sales are up but there are big problems
in Europe. We need continuity. Mr Clarke must do nothing to upset shaky
confidence.'
Mr Alec McKee, managing director of the UK arm of John Deere, the US
agricultural equipment makers, based in the village of Langar, said:
'Uncertainty is the enemy of investment.'
Mr McKee reports a 20 per cent increase in sales this year but remains
uncertain about recovery: 'At this stage, any increase in the tax burden,
direct or indirect, will be harmful to consumer demand. The less Mr Clarke
does in the short term the better.'
He said the temporary improvement in capital allowances announced in the
last Budget should be maintained, but insists interest rates have fallen far
enough.
The 'hands off interest rates' campaign is joined by Mr John Wood, a
Cotgrave resident, Tory party activist, fabric manufacturer and master of
the Worshipful Company of Glovers.
Mr Wood, who helped select Mr Clarke for the Rushcliffe seat in 1970, says
lower interest rates would not help British companies sell in important
European markets where customers are not buying.
Outside the post office in Clifton, a neat thatched village, Mrs Audrey
Welling, a Tory-voting retired legal clerk, is one of many to round on the
chancellor's plans for putting value added tax on heating fuel.
She said: 'He will commit suicide. People will remember every time they pay
the bill. The government will live to regret it even more than us.'
</TEXT>
