<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Industry will argue against tax increases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRIALISTS are expected to put more pressure on the government this week
to refrain from increasing taxes in next month's Budget on the grounds that
this would damage faltering signs of an upturn.
The message is to be delivered at a private meeting on Thursday between
Treasury and Department of Trade and Industry officials and representatives
of about 20 companies including Grand Metropolitan, TI, Unigate, Marks and
Spencer, J. Sainsbury, British Steel and Barclays Bank.
The gathering is expected to feature arguments that any rise in taxes in the
November 30 Budget, coming on top of tax increases of nearly Pounds 7bn
already announced for next April, might damage confidence and delay the
recovery.
Two Treasury officials at the meeting will relay any substantive messages to
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor.
Government figures on Friday showed that the pace of growth in non-oil gross
domestic product slowed in the third quarter of this year.
Chairman of Thursday's gathering will be Mr Walter Eltis, economic adviser
to Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary. It is being held
as part of a general effort by the government to form closer links with
companies to follow better their perceptions about the recovery.
The most senior person from the business world will be Mr David Barnes,
chief executive of Zeneca, formerly the speciality chemicals subsidiary of
ICI. Northern Foods, the Weir pumpmaking company, ICL, Rover and the Meggitt
engineering group are due to send their finance directors. Other businesses
to be represented at the meeting are Courtaulds Textiles, George Wimpey and
the Post Office.
Executives from the companies involved have fed data to Mr Eltis to enable
him to gain a better feel of the recovery independently of the Treasury.
Mr Christopher Haskins, chairman of Northern Foods, who has been closely
involved with Mr Eltis's project, said he was 'extremely nervous' about the
recovery. Mr Martin Beer, a Unigate executive, said the business world was
worried about tax increases.
Mr Clarke is meeting Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation
of British Industry, and Sir Michael Angus, CBI president, at the Treasury
on Wednesday to hear their ideas for his Budget strategy. They are expected
to add to warnings about how tax rises could harm business.
</TEXT>
