<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Building chiefs warn of job losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT LEAST 100,000 further jobs could be lost in the construction industry if
next month's Budget fails to maintain capital spending, industry leaders
have warned.
Mr Ian Dixon, chairman of the Construction Industry Council, and Mr Tony
Jackson, chairman of the Construction Industry Employers Council, said the
'unique spectre' of a second Budget in one year had restricted the
industry's recovery.
They said any improvement in this recovery was so fragile that it could
easily be shattered if there were signs of reductions in capital spending.
'More time is needed for the private sector to recover,' they said.
Employment in the construction industry has fallen by more than 500,000
since the middle of 1989.
They also warned that the prospect of private-sector finance going into
public works was still distant, although the idea was strongly supported by
the industry.
There were fears in the industry that privately funded schemes might be seen
as an opportunity to replace publicly financed infrastructure projects, when
they should be used to accelerate infrastructure improvement.
Meanwhile, the Federation of Master Builders reported a small improvement in
workloads in its third-quarter state of trade survey.
It said 18 per cent of companies reported an increase in work, 55 per cent
stayed at the same level, and 27 per cent recorded a decrease. The
second-quarter figures were 15, 55 and 30 per cent respectively.
Mr Ted Evans, national president, said the improvement came mainly among
companies doing repair and maintenance work.
He added: 'However, the reports of improvement are so lean and patchy that
little or no encouragement can be drawn from the figures.'
