<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Major rejects US view on Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday re-opened the transatlantic war of words over the
west's approach to Bosnia by rejecting demands from Washington for a lifting
of the arms embargo, Philip Stephens writes.
In a brusque dismissal of recent public criticism by the US of Britain's
stance, the prime minister directly contradicted comments by President Bill
Clinton.
Mr Major denied he had told Mr Clinton that he would find it impossible to
sustain his government if he acceded to US requests to allow the resumption
of arms sales to the Bosnian Moslems. Instead he had simply pointed out
there was no political support for the idea in the UK.
Displaying some irritation, the prime minister suggested that criticism by
Mr Warren Christopher, the US secretary of state, of Europe's role in
preserving international peace reflected the US administration's domestic
problems.
He said on BBC Television that a resumption of arms supplies to the warring
factions in the former Yugoslav province would add to the bloodshed. It
would also end the humanitarian aid effort.
He added: 'I believe the policy we are adopting in Bosnia is the right one.
I know it is controversial. That does not mean it is wrong. We have done
more in Bosnia than any other great nation and we will continue.'
Mr Major rejected suggestions that the difference over Bosnia had damaged
irreparably Britain's relationship with the Clinton administration.
</TEXT>
