<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 93 / Number of women directors on the increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of women directors and executives has begun to creep up while the
number of accountants in these positions has dropped sharply, according to a
survey by Hemmington Scott, the corporate information publishers, Andrew
Jack writes.
Just 3.6 per cent of the 12,310 executives and officers of quoted companies
are women, although the proportion has increased from less than 2.7 per cent
four years ago. The number with fellowships of the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales has declined from 1,721 to 1,448 over the
same period.
The number of directors and executives who are masters of business
administration has increased from none to more than 100 since 1989, with
Harvard proving the most popular of the business schools.
The most frequent jobs for women in senior business positions are in finance
and administration. There are 16 finance directors and a quarter of the
women identified are chief accountants or company secretaries. Nearly half
of the 442 women identified in the survey as in senior positions are board
members.
More than 700 directors are aged over 65, and 654 have been awarded some
form of honour.
Arthur Andersen Corporate Register. Hemmington Scott Publishing, 26-31
Whiskin Street, London EC1R 0BP. Pounds 150 annually.
</TEXT>
